05686nam a22006975i 9780822378822DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223788227 a10.1515/97808223788222doi  a(DE-B1597)552542  a(OCoLC)846472925  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0270702bisacsh04a907.2222//gereng00aFour Decades On :bVietnam, the United States, and the Legacies of the Second Indochina War /ced. by Edwin A. Martini, Edwin A. Martini, Scott Laderman. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b14 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: National Amnesia, Transnational Memory, and the Legacies of the Second Indochina War -- t1. Legacies Foretold -- t2. Viet Nam and “Vietnam” in American History and Memory -- t3. “The Mainspring in This Country Has Been Broken” -- t4. Cold War in a Vietnamese Community -- t5. The Ambivalence of Reconciliation in Contemporary Vietnamese Memoryscape -- t6. Remembering War, Dreaming Peace -- t7. Việt Nam’s Growing Pains -- t8. A Fishy Affair -- t9. Agent Orange -- t10. Refuge to Refuse -- t11. Missing in Action in the Twenty-First Century -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Four Decades On, historians, anthropologists, and literary critics examine the legacies of the Second Indochina War, or what most Americans call the Vietnam War, nearly forty years after the United States finally left Vietnam. They address matters such as the daunting tasks facing the Vietnamese at the war's end—including rebuilding a nation and consolidating a socialist revolution while fending off China and the Khmer Rouge—and "the Vietnam syndrome," the cynical, frustrated, and pessimistic sense that colored America's views of the rest of the world after its humiliating defeat in Vietnam. The contributors provide unexpected perspectives on Agent Orange, the POW/MIA controversies, the commercial trade relationship between the United States and Vietnam, and representations of the war and its aftermath produced by artists, particularly writers. They show how the war has continued to affect not only international relations but also the everyday lives of millions of people around the world. Most of the contributors take up matters in the United States, Vietnam, or both nations, while several utilize transnational analytic frameworks, recognizing that the war's legacies shape and are shaped by dynamics that transcend the two countries.Contributors. Alex Bloom, Diane Niblack Fox, H. Bruce Franklin, Walter Hixson, Heonik Kwon, Scott Laderman, Mariam B. Lam, Ngo Vinh Long, Edwin A. Martini, Viet Thanh Nguyen, Christina Schwenkel, Charles Waugh  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xInfluence. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zUnited States. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zVietnam. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh1 aBloom, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, H. Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHixson, Walter L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwon, Heonik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaderman, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaderman, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLam, Mariam B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Ngo Vinh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartini, Edwin A., 